# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: arctic
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:arctic/1st-soviet-antarctic-expedition] The **First Soviet Antarctic Expedition** was a 1955–1957 expedition to Antarctica by explorers from the Soviet Union, led by Mikhail Somov.
[src:arctic/1st-soviet-antarctic-expedition] The principal task of the expedition was to organise the main base, Mirny, and perform limited scientific observations.
[src:arctic/1st-soviet-antarctic-expedition] Other tasks were reconnaissance of sites for the inland bases Vostok and Sovetskaya; and oceanography of the Indian Ocean.
[src:arctic/1st-soviet-antarctic-expedition] The expedition lasted from 30 November 1955 to 1957, and involved 127 expedition members and 75 crew members.
[src:arctic/1st-soviet-antarctic-expedition] It was led by Mikhail Somov, while his scientific deputy was V.
[src:arctic/1st-soviet-antarctic-expedition] Suzyumov; also spelt Yevgeny or Eugene Suzyumov) was the scientific secretary of the expedition.
[src:arctic/1st-soviet-antarctic-expedition] He later organised and participated in many other research expeditions to the Arctic, Antarctic, Atlantic, Indian, and Pacific Oceans, as well as authoring 13 popular science and history books, and many articles about the war in the Arctic and oceanographic studies.
[src:arctic/1st-soviet-antarctic-expedition] He was the recipient of seven awards and 14 medals.
[src:arctic/1st-soviet-antarctic-expedition] At a special meeting of the Soviet Geographical Society in October 1958 which paid tribute to the memory of Australian geologist and Antarctic explorer Douglas Mawson, Suzyumov said that Mawson had developed friendships with Soviet Antarctic explorers in his later years.
[src:arctic/1st-soviet-antarctic-expedition] Suzyumov later wrote *Zhizn, otdannaia Antarktide*, translated as *A life given to the Antarctic: Douglas Mawson – Antarctic explorer*, published in 1968.
[src:arctic/1st-soviet-antarctic-expedition] Three diesel-electric ships were used to transport the expedition.
[src:arctic/1st-soviet-antarctic-expedition] The final ship was used only for transporting perishables.
[src:arctic/1st-soviet-antarctic-expedition] *Ob* and *Lena* were icebreakers 130m long and displacing 12,600 tons.
[src:arctic/1st-soviet-antarctic-expedition] On 30 November 1955 *Ob* left port at Kaliningrad.
[src:arctic/2nd-soviet-antarctic-expedition] The **Second Soviet Antarctic Expedition** was led by Aleksei Treshnikov on the continent; the marine expedition on the "Ob" was led by I.
[src:arctic/2nd-soviet-antarctic-expedition] The "Ob" left Kaliningrad on 7 November, 1956.
[src:arctic/2nd-soviet-antarctic-expedition] Three ships were used to transport the expedition, all diesel-electric.
[src:arctic/2nd-soviet-antarctic-expedition] The two main ships were as for the first expedition: RV *Ob* (flagship; captain I.
[src:arctic/2nd-soviet-antarctic-expedition] The third ship was *Kooperatsiya* (captain A.
[src:arctic/2nd-soviet-antarctic-expedition] Yantselevich), used mainly as a transport vessel.
[src:arctic/2nd-soviet-antarctic-expedition] Full scale scientific work for the International Geophysical Year (IGY) This included glacier mapping and wildlife tracking, among other things.
[src:arctic/3rd-soviet-antarctic-expedition] The **Third Soviet Antarctic Expedition** (1957–59) was led by Yevgeny Tolstikov on the continent and included Czech future astronomer Antonín Mrkos; the marine expedition on the *Ob* was led by I V Maksimov.
[src:arctic/3rd-soviet-antarctic-expedition] Two diesel-electric ships were used to transport the expedition.
[src:arctic/3rd-soviet-antarctic-expedition] Man) and *Kooperatsiya* (captain A S Yantselevich), used mainly as a transport vessel.
[src:arctic/3rd-soviet-antarctic-expedition] The ships arrived in Antarctica in November – December 1957.
[src:arctic/3rd-soviet-antarctic-expedition] Together with the ships' crews the expedition consisted of 445 men, of whom 183 were scheduled for wintering.
[src:arctic/3rd-soviet-antarctic-expedition] The programme included 6 stations: (Mirny; Vostok; Sovetskaya; Oasis; Pionerskaya and Komsomol'skaya).
[src:arctic/3rd-soviet-antarctic-expedition] The first tractor-train to the interior left on 26 December, with 32 men.
[src:arctic/3rd-soviet-antarctic-expedition] On 2 January 1958 the train arrived at Pionerskaya, and left again on the 8th.
[src:arctic/3rd-soviet-antarctic-expedition] On the 17th they reached Komsomol'skaya; conditions of travel were difficult.
[src:arctic/3rd-soviet-antarctic-expedition] A portion of the train (7 tractors and sledges) left on the 20th to relieve Vostok, arriving on the 27th, and delivering over 100 tons of cargo.
[src:arctic/3rd-soviet-antarctic-expedition] On the 28th the train left for Komsomol'skaya, arriving on the 31st.
[src:arctic/3rd-soviet-antarctic-expedition] On 3 February the train, with 27 men, left to found Sovetskaya; they reached 78° 24′ S, 87° 35′ E on the 10th, at an altitude of 3570 m.
[src:arctic/3rd-soviet-antarctic-expedition] The station was rapidly constructed, and the train left on the 18th, returning to Mirny on 4 March, having completed a round trip of 4,000 km (2,500 mi).
[src:arctic/3rd-soviet-antarctic-expedition] After spending the Antarctic winter at Mirny, the Expedition undertook a second set of tractor traverses starting in September 1958.
[src:arctic/3rd-soviet-antarctic-expedition] One team reached the pole of inaccessibility and established The Pole of Inaccessibility station there on 14 December.
[src:arctic/3rd-soviet-antarctic-expedition] Estonian writer Juhan Smuul took part of the expedition as a Soviet journalist and described the interesting details in his 1960 book "Antarctica Ahoy!: The Ice Book" ("Jäine raamat" in Estonian).
[src:arctic/a-greek-english-lexicon] It was most recently revised for its ninth edition of 1940.
[src:arctic/a-greek-english-lexicon] Abridged versions and a supplement exist.
[src:arctic/a-greek-english-lexicon] It was initially the basis for the 2021 *Cambridge Greek Lexicon*, although subsequently that became a complete rewrite from scratch.
[src:arctic/a-greek-english-lexicon] The lexicon was begun in the 19th century, and is now in its ninth (revised) edition, published in 1940.
[src:arctic/a-greek-english-lexicon] It was based on the earlier *Handwörterbuch der griechischen Sprache* by the German lexicographer Franz Passow (first published in 1819, fourth edition 1831), which in turn was based on Johann Gottlob Schneider's *Kritisches griechisch-deutsches Handwörterbuch*.
[src:arctic/a-greek-english-lexicon] The *Lexicon* has served as the basis for all later lexicographical work on the ancient Greek language, such as the ongoing Greek–Spanish dictionary project *Diccionario Griego–Español* (DGE).
[src:arctic/a-greek-english-lexicon] It is now conventionally referred to as *Liddell & Scott*, *Liddell–Scott–Jones*, or *LSJ*, and its three sizes are sometimes referred to as "The Little Liddell", "The Middle Liddell" and "The Big Liddell" or "The Great Scott".
[src:arctic/a-greek-english-lexicon] The LSJ main edition has 116,502 entries.
[src:arctic/a-greek-english-lexicon] According to Stuart Jones's preface to the ninth (1925) edition, the creation of the *Lexicon* was originally proposed by David Alphonso Talboys, an Oxford publisher.
[src:arctic/a-greek-english-lexicon] It was published by the Clarendon Press at Oxford rather than by Talboys, who died before the first edition (1843) was complete.
[src:arctic/a-greek-english-lexicon] The first editor of the LSJ, Henry George Liddell, was Dean of Christ Church, Oxford, and the father of Alice Liddell, the eponymous Alice of the writings of Lewis Carroll.
[src:arctic/a-greek-english-lexicon] The eighth edition (1897) was the last edition published during Liddell's lifetime.
[src:arctic/a-greek-english-lexicon] The LSJ is sometimes compared and contrasted with *A Latin Dictionary* by Lewis and Short, which was also published by Oxford University Press (OUP).
[src:arctic/a-greek-english-lexicon] It is also sometimes compared with the Bauer lexicon, which is a similar work focused on the Greek of the New Testament.
[src:arctic/a-greek-english-lexicon] The LSJ's definitions reflect the Victorian morality of its time, using euphemism.
[src:arctic/a-greek-english-lexicon] For example, χέζω (*chezo*, 'to shit'), is translated as "ease oneself, do one's need"; βινέω (*bineo*, 'to fuck') as "inire, coire, of illicit intercourse"; and λαικάζω (*laikazo*, 'to suck cocks') as "to wench".
[src:arctic/a-greek-english-lexicon] Two condensed editions of LSJ were published by Oxford University Press and remain in print.
[src:arctic/a-greek-english-lexicon] In 1843, the same year as the full lexicon's publication, *A Lexicon: Abridged from Liddell and Scott's Greek–English Lexicon*, sometimes called "the Little Liddell" was published.
[src:arctic/a-greek-english-lexicon] For example, a reprint, re-typeset in 2007, of the 1909 edition is available from Simon Wallenberg Press.
[src:arctic/a-greek-english-lexicon] In 1889, an intermediate edition of the lexicon, *An Intermediate Greek–English Lexicon*, was prepared on the basis of the seventh edition (1883) of LSJ.
[src:arctic/a-greek-english-lexicon] After the publication of the ninth edition in 1940, and shortly after the deaths of both Stuart Jones and McKenzie, the OUP maintained a list of *addenda et corrigenda* ("additions and corrections"), which was bound with subsequent printings.
[src:arctic/a-greek-english-lexicon] However, in 1968, these were replaced by a Supplement to the LSJ.
[src:arctic/a-greek-english-lexicon] Neither the *addenda* nor the Supplement has ever been merged into the main text, which still stands as originally composed by Liddell, Scott, Jones, and McKenzie.
[src:arctic/a-greek-english-lexicon] The Supplement was initially edited by M.
[src:arctic/a-greek-english-lexicon] Glare, editor of the *Oxford Latin Dictionary* (not to be confused with Lewis and Short's *A Latin Dictionary*).
[src:arctic/a-greek-english-lexicon] Since 1988, it has been edited by Glare and Anne A.
[src:arctic/a-greek-english-lexicon] As the title page of the *Lexicon* makes clear (and the prefaces to the main text and to the Supplement attest), this editorial work has been performed "with the cooperation of many scholars".
[src:arctic/a-greek-english-lexicon] The Supplement primarily takes the form of a list of additions and corrections to the main text, sorted by entry.
[src:arctic/a-greek-english-lexicon] The supplemental entries are marked with signs to show the nature of the changes they call for.
[src:arctic/a-greek-english-lexicon] Thus, a user of the *Lexicon* can consult the Supplement after consulting the main text to see whether scholarship after Jones and McKenzie has provided any new information about a particular word.
[src:arctic/a-greek-english-lexicon] As of 2005, the most recent revision of the Supplement, published in 1996, contains 320 pages of corrections to the main text, as well as other materials.
[src:arctic/a-greek-english-lexicon] The small "x" indicates that this word did not appear in the main text at all; "S.*fr*." refers to the collected fragmentary works of Sophocles.
[src:arctic/a-greek-english-lexicon] One interesting new source of lexicographic material in the revised Supplement is the Mycenean inscriptions.
[src:arctic/a-greek-english-lexicon] The ninth edition of LSJ has been freely available in electronic form since 2007, having been digitized by the Perseus Project.
[src:arctic/a-greek-english-lexicon] Diogenes, a free software package, incorporates the Perseus data and allows easy offline consultation of LSJ on Mac OS X, Windows, and Linux platforms.
[src:arctic/a-greek-english-lexicon] Marcion is another open source application that includes the Perseus LSJ.
[src:arctic/a-greek-english-lexicon] For mobile devices, both the Kindle E-Ink and the iPhone/iPod Touch feature data ported from Perseus.
[src:arctic/a-greek-english-lexicon] The Android market also currently offers the intermediate LSJ as an offline downloadable app for free or for a small price.
[src:arctic/a-greek-english-lexicon] A CD-ROM version published and sold by Logos Bible Software also incorporates the Supplement's additions to the ninth edition of LSJ.
[src:arctic/a-greek-english-lexicon] A new online version of LSJ was released in 2011 by the Thesaurus Linguae Graecae (TLG).
[src:arctic/a-greek-english-lexicon] The TLG version corrects "a large number of typographical errors", and includes links to the extensive TLG textual corpus.
[src:arctic/a-greek-english-lexicon] A Kindle version, the "Complete Liddell & Scott's Lexicon with Inflections", is also available: it allows searches of most Classical Greek word-forms and supports a growing number of Ancient/Classical Greek texts for the device.
[src:arctic/a-greek-english-lexicon] The Lexicon has been translated into Modern Greek by Xenophon Moschos, ed.: Michael Konstantinidis and was published by Anestis Konstantinidis in 1904 with the title *H.
[src:arctic/a-greek-english-lexicon] Scott – Α.* Κωνσταντινίδου (Μέγα Λεξικόν τῆς Ἑλληνικῆς Γλώσσης).
[src:arctic/a-greek-english-lexicon] Also, a supplement compiled by a group of Greek philologists.
[src:arctic/a-greek-english-lexicon] An Italian translation of the *Intermediate Liddell-Scott*, entitled *Dizionario illustrato Greco-Italiano* was published in 1975 by Le Monnier, edited by Q.
[src:arctic/a-greek-english-lexicon] LSJ was the basis of the project of John Chadwick and James Diggle at Cambridge to publish the *Cambridge Greek Lexicon* of 2021.
[src:arctic/a-greek-english-lexicon] Although it was initially conceived as a mere update of LSJ, the editors eventually decided to start afresh since they considered LSJ "too antiquated in concept, design and content".
[src:arctic/a-greek-english-lexicon] The CGL has a smaller scope than the LSJ (and also the *Brill Dictionary of Ancient Greek*), and is unlikely to replace it; however, it is still more comprehensive than the Middle Liddell, which it intends to replace.
[src:arctic/a-greek-english-lexicon] The *Cambridge Greek Lexicon* uses contemporary language for its definitions and, unlike the LSJ, no longer elides the meaning of words considered offensive in Victorian times.
[src:arctic/a-sibiryakov-icebreaker] The ship was recorded as *Bellaventure* until at least 1920.
[src:arctic/a-sibiryakov-icebreaker] By 1927 she had been renamed *Александр Сибиряков*.
[src:arctic/a-sibiryakov-icebreaker] In the Latin alphabet her name was rendered ***Alexander Sibiriakov*** until at least 1935.
[src:arctic/a-sibiryakov-icebreaker] This had been changed to *Alexander Sibiryakov* by 1939.
[src:arctic/a-sibiryakov-icebreaker] In 1908 A Harvey & Co of St John's, Newfoundland ordered a pair of ships from shipbuilders in Glasgow, Scotland.
[src:arctic/a-sibiryakov-icebreaker] D&W Henderson Ltd built *Bellaventure*, launching her on 23 November 1908.
[src:arctic/a-sibiryakov-icebreaker] Napier and Miller built her sister ship *Bonaventure*, launching her on 5 December 1908.
[src:arctic/a-sibiryakov-icebreaker] Both ships were completed in January 1909.
[src:arctic/a-sibiryakov-icebreaker] On 2 April 1914 *Bellaventure*, commanded by Captain Isaac Randell, was off the northern coast of Newfoundland taking part in a seal hunt.
[src:arctic/a-sibiryakov-icebreaker] 132 hunters from another steamship, *Newfoundland*, had become lost in a storm on an ice floe.
[src:arctic/a-sibiryakov-icebreaker] After 54 hours *Bellaventure* rescued the survivors and recovered 77 dead bodies.
[src:arctic/a-sibiryakov-icebreaker] John's, Newfoundland, with her flags at half mast.
[src:arctic/a-sibiryakov-icebreaker] In 1917 the Russian government bought both *Bellaventure* and *Bonaventure*.
[src:arctic/a-sibiryakov-icebreaker] In 1919, in the North Russia intervention in the Russian Civil War, United Kingdom forces in Arkhangelsk took control of both ships, and Ellerman's Wilson Line was appointed to manage *Bellaventure*.
[src:arctic/a-sibiryakov-icebreaker] Eventually the two ships were renamed *Alexander Sibiryakov* and *Vladimir Rusanov*, after two Russian arctic explorers.
[src:arctic/a-sibiryakov-icebreaker] On 24 November 1936 *Alexander Sibiryakov* was stranded near Cape Menshikov in the Kara Sea.
[src:arctic/a-sibiryakov-icebreaker] She was refloated on 25 December 1936 and returned to service in June 1938.
[src:arctic/a-sibiryakov-icebreaker] In September 1941 the Soviet Navy requisitioned *Alexander Sibiryakov*.
[src:arctic/a-sibiryakov-icebreaker] She continued in service, commanded by Captain Anatoli Kacharava.
[src:arctic/a-sibiryakov-icebreaker] She was defensively armed, at first with several 76 mm (3 in) and 45 mm (2 in) guns.
[src:arctic/a-sibiryakov-icebreaker] By 1942 one 4 in (102 mm) gun had been added.
[src:arctic/a-sibiryakov-icebreaker] On 25 August 1942 during Operation Wunderland the Kriegsmarine heavy cruiser *Admiral Scheer* attacked her off the northwest shore of Russky Island in the Nordenskiöld Archipelago.
[src:arctic/a-sibiryakov-icebreaker] Despite being heavily outgunned, *Alexander Sibiryakov* managed to defend herself for an hour before *Admiral Scheer* sank her.
[src:arctic/a-sibiryakov-icebreaker] *Alexander Sibiryakov* also sent a wireless telegraph signal that warned east and west bound Allied convoys of the attacks, enabling them to avoid the area.
[src:arctic/a-sibiryakov-icebreaker] Most members of *Alexander Sibiryakov*'s crew were killed either in battle or when she sank.
[src:arctic/a-sibiryakov-icebreaker] *Admiral Scheer* captured 22, including severely wounded Captain Kacharava.
[src:arctic/a-sibiryakov-icebreaker] One crewman, stoker Pavel Vavilov, managed to reach Beluha Island and was rescued by a Soviet ship 34 or 35 days later.
[src:arctic/a-sibiryakov-icebreaker] Due to the genocidal Nazi policies towards captured Soviet POWs, only 15 crew members survived the war.
[src:arctic/a-sibiryakov-icebreaker] Soviet sources say 79 killed, 19 taken as prisoners of war, and only 13 of them survived captivity.
[src:arctic/a-sibiryakov-icebreaker] The Soviet Union later sent several expedition to locate the wreck of the ship, including one in 1982, but none had achieved success.
[src:arctic/a-sibiryakov-icebreaker] It was finally located in 2014 by a research expedition organized by a Russian private company 'Fertoing', and in 2015 the wreck was explored by a remotely operated underwater vehicle and divers, who collected some of the ship's parts as museum exhibits.
[src:arctic/a-sibiryakov-icebreaker] A memorial plaque was affixed to the ship's hull in memory of the perished sailors.
[src:arctic/a-sibiryakov-icebreaker] On April 29, 1961, a Decree of the Presidium of the Supreme Soviet of the USSR awarded a number of crew members of the Alexander Sibiryakov "for the courage and fortitude shown by the crew members of the Order of the Red Banner icebreaker steamship *A.
[src:arctic/a-sibiryakov-icebreaker] Kacharava, being awarded the Order of the Red Banner.
[src:arctic/a-sibiryakov-icebreaker] Long before this, even during the war years, a tradition had developed of ships lowering their flags and sounding their horns in salute when passing through this location.
[src:arctic/a-sibiryakov-icebreaker] In 1945, the name *Sibiryakov* was given to the Finnish icebreaker *Jääkarhu* (built 1926), received from Finland as war reparations.
[src:arctic/a-sibiryakov-icebreaker] In honor of the icebreaker's crew, a strait in the Kara Sea north of Dikson Island was named the Sibiryakovtsev Strait.
[src:arctic/a-sibiryakov-icebreaker] The ship's name is also borne by a shoal in the Barents Sea near Novaya Zemlya and a mountain in Antarctica on Enderby Land.
[src:arctic/a-sibiryakov-icebreaker] On Belukha Island (Elimelakh Island), a lighthouse was erected in memory of the ship's feat.
[src:arctic/ad-dahna-desert] The desert is a series of seven successive deserts, separated from one another by plains.
[src:arctic/ad-dahna-desert] Roads pass through Al-Dahnā, linking Kuwait with Al-Zilfī and Riyadh and connecting Riyadh with Hasa.
[src:arctic/ad-dahna-desert] Ad-Dahna desert is formed of high sand dunes spreading horizontally which are called ergs (Arabic: عِرْق, romanized: *ʿirq*), mostly red in color since it contains Iron Oxides.
[src:arctic/ad-dahna-desert] Beneath the harsh deserts of Saudi Arabia lie dark chambers and complex mazes filled with crystalline structures, stalactites and stalagmites.
[src:arctic/ad-dahna-desert] The limestone floor of the Summan plateau, a karst area to the east of the ad-Dahna desert, is riddled with such caves, known locally as *Dahls*.
[src:arctic/ad-dahna-desert] Some have tiny entrances which open into caves, others lead into a maze of passages which can be several kilometers long.
[src:arctic/ad-dahna-desert] Local Bedouin have always known these caves and some were used as water supplies.
[src:arctic/ad-dahna-desert] They were first systematically studied in the 1981, and later explored and reported by the Saudi Geological Survey.
[src:arctic/adolf-erik-nordenskiöld] Born in the Grand Duchy of Finland in the Russian Empire, he was forced to move to Sweden in 1857 due to his political activity, where he became a member of the Parliament of Sweden and of the Swedish Academy.
[src:arctic/adolf-erik-nordenskiöld] He led the *Vega* Expedition along the northern coast of Eurasia in 1878–1879.
[src:arctic/adolf-erik-nordenskiöld] This was the first complete crossing of the Northeast Passage.
[src:arctic/adolf-erik-nordenskiöld] Initially a troubled enterprise, the successful expedition is considered to be among the highest achievements in the history of Swedish science.
[src:arctic/adolf-erik-nordenskiöld] The Nordenskiölds were an old Fenno-Swedish family, and members of the nobility.
[src:arctic/adolf-erik-nordenskiöld] Nordenskiöld's father, Nils Gustaf Nordenskiöld, was a Finnish mineralogist, civil servant and traveller.
[src:arctic/adolf-erik-nordenskiöld] He was also a member of the Russian Academy of Sciences.
[src:arctic/adolf-erik-nordenskiöld] Adolf Erik was the father of Gustaf Nordenskiöld (explorer of Mesa Verde) and Erland Nordenskiöld (ethnographer of South America) and maternal uncle of Nils Otto Gustaf Nordenskjöld (another polar explorer).
[src:arctic/adolf-erik-nordenskiöld] Nils Otto Gustaf Nordenskjöld's parents were cousins — Otto Gustaf Nordenskjöld (born in 1831 in Hässleby, Sweden) and Anna Elisabet Sofia Nordenskiöld (born in 1841 in Finland), who was the sister of Adolf Erik Nordenskiöld.
[src:arctic/adolf-erik-nordenskiöld] The Swedish side of the family used the spelling "Nordenskjöld", whereas the Finnish side of the family used the "Nordenskiöld" spelling.
[src:arctic/adolf-erik-nordenskiöld] His nephew Erik Nordenskiöld became a zoologist and historian of biology.
[src:arctic/adolf-erik-nordenskiöld] Nordenskiöld was born in 1832 in Helsinki, the capital of Finland, but he spent his early youth on the family estate, the Frugård Manor, located in the Numminen village in Mäntsälä.
[src:arctic/adolf-erik-nordenskiöld] He went to school in Porvoo, a small town on the south coast of Finland.
[src:arctic/adolf-erik-nordenskiöld] He then entered the Imperial Alexander University in Helsinki in 1849 where he studied mathematics, geology, and applied himself especially to chemistry and mineralogy.
[src:arctic/adolf-erik-nordenskiöld] He received his master's degree in 1853.
[src:arctic/adolf-erik-nordenskiöld] Two years later he published his doctoral dissertation, entitled *"Om grafitens och chondroditens kristallformer"* ("On the crystal forms of graphite and chondrodite").
[src:arctic/adolf-erik-nordenskiöld] Upon his graduation, in 1853, Nordenskiöld accompanied his father to the Ural Mountains and studied the iron and copper mines at Tagilsk; on his return he received minor appointments both at the university and the mining office.
[src:arctic/adolf-erik-nordenskiöld] Having studied under Johan Ludvig Runeberg, Nordenskiöld belonged to Liberal, anti-tsarist circles that agitated for Finland's liberation from Russia by the Swedes during the Crimean War.
[src:arctic/adolf-erik-nordenskiöld] An unguarded speech at a convivial entertainment in 1855 drew the attention of the Imperial Russian authorities to his political views, and led to a dismissal from the university.
[src:arctic/adolf-erik-nordenskiöld] He then visited Berlin, continuing his mineralogical studies, and in 1856 obtained a travelling stipend from the university in Helsinki and planned to expend it in geological research in Siberia and Kamchatka.
[src:arctic/adolf-erik-nordenskiöld] In 1856, Nordenskiöld was also appointed Docent in Mineralogy at the university.
[src:arctic/adolf-erik-nordenskiöld] In 1857 he aroused the suspicion of the authorities again, so that he was forced to leave Finland, practically as a political refugee, and was deprived of the right of ever holding office in the university of Finland.
[src:arctic/adolf-erik-nordenskiöld] In 1862, he was one of the founding members of Sällskapet Idun, a men's association founded in Stockholm.
[src:arctic/adolf-erik-nordenskiöld] In 1863 he married Anna Maria Mannerheim, the aunt of Marshal C.
[src:arctic/adolf-erik-nordenskiöld] Nordenskiöld settled in Stockholm, and soon he received an offer from Otto Torell, a geologist, to accompany him on an expedition to Spitsbergen.
[src:arctic/adolf-erik-nordenskiöld] He was also awarded the 1869 Royal Geographical Society's Founder's Medal.
[src:arctic/adolf-erik-nordenskiöld] Nordenskiöld's participation in three geological expeditions to Spitsbergen, followed by longer Arctic explorations in 1867, 1870, 1872 and 1875, led him to attempt the discovery of the long-sought Northeast Passage.
[src:arctic/adolf-erik-nordenskiöld] This he accomplished in the voyage of the *SS Vega*, navigating for the first time the northern coasts of Europe and Asia.
[src:arctic/adolf-erik-nordenskiöld] Starting from Karlskrona on 22 June 1878, the *Vega* doubled Cape Chelyuskin in the following August, and after being frozen in at the end of September near the Bering Strait, completed the voyage successfully in the following summer.
[src:arctic/adolf-erik-nordenskiöld] He edited a monumental record of the expedition in five volumes, and himself wrote a more popular summary in two volumes.
[src:arctic/adolf-erik-nordenskiöld] On his return to Sweden he received an enthusiastic welcome, and in April 1880 was made a baron and a commander of the Order of the North Star.
[src:arctic/adolf-erik-nordenskiöld] In 1883, he visited the east coast of Greenland for the second time, and succeeded in taking his ship through the great ice barrier, a feat attempted in vain during more than three centuries.
[src:arctic/adolf-erik-nordenskiöld] The captain on the *Vega* expedition, Louis Palander, was made a nobleman at the same time, and took the name *Palander af Vega*.
[src:arctic/adolf-erik-nordenskiöld] In 1893, Nordenskiöld was elected to the 12th chair of the Swedish Academy.
[src:arctic/adolf-erik-nordenskiöld] In 1900 he received the Murchison Medal from the Geological Society of London.
[src:arctic/adolf-erik-nordenskiöld] He was nominated for the first Nobel Prize in Physics but died before the prizes were awarded.
[src:arctic/adolf-erik-nordenskiöld] Nordenskiöld died on 12 August 1901, in Dalbyö, Södermanland, Sweden, at the age of 68.
[src:arctic/adolf-erik-nordenskiöld] As an explorer, Nordenskiöld was interested in the history of Arctic exploration, especially as evidenced in old maps.
[src:arctic/adolf-erik-nordenskiöld] This interest in turn led him to collect and systematically study early maps.
[src:arctic/adolf-erik-nordenskiöld] He left his huge personal collection of early maps to the University of Helsinki, and it was inscribed on UNESCO's Memory of the World International Register in 1997.
[src:arctic/arctic] The **Arctic** (/ˈɑːr(k)tɪk/; from Ancient Greek ἄρκτος*(*árktos*)* 'bear') is the polar region of Earth that surrounds the North Pole, lying north of the Arctic Circle.
[src:arctic/arctic] Land within the Arctic region has seasonally varying snow and ice cover, with predominantly treeless permafrost under the tundra.
[src:arctic/arctic] Arctic seas contain seasonal sea ice in many places.
[src:arctic/arctic] The Arctic region is a unique area among Earth's ecosystems.
[src:arctic/arctic] The cultures in the region and the Arctic indigenous peoples have adapted to its cold and extreme conditions.
[src:arctic/arctic] Life in the Arctic includes zooplankton and phytoplankton, fish and marine mammals, birds, land animals, plants, and human societies.
[src:arctic/arctic] Arctic land is bordered by the subarctic.
[src:arctic/arctic] There are several definitions of what area is contained within the Arctic.
[src:arctic/arctic] The area can be defined as north of the Arctic Circle (about 66° 34'N), the approximate southern limit of the midnight sun and the polar night.
[src:arctic/arctic] Another definition of the Arctic, which is popular with ecologists, is the region in the Northern Hemisphere where the average temperature for the warmest month (July) is below 10 °C (50 °F); the northernmost tree line roughly follows the isotherm at the boundary of this region.
[src:arctic/arctic] The climate of the Arctic region is characterized by cold winters and cool summers.
[src:arctic/arctic] Its precipitation mostly comes in the form of snow and is low, with most of the area receiving less than 50 cm (20 in).
[src:arctic/arctic] High winds often stir up snow, creating the illusion of continuous snowfall.
[src:arctic/arctic] Average winter temperatures can go as low as −40 °C (−40 °F), and the coldest recorded temperature is approximately −68 °C (−90 °F).
[src:arctic/arctic] Coastal Arctic climates are moderated by oceanic influences, having generally warmer temperatures and heavier snowfalls than the colder and drier interior areas.
[src:arctic/arctic] The Arctic is affected by current global warming, leading to climate change in the Arctic, including Arctic sea ice decline, diminished ice in the Greenland ice sheet, and Arctic methane emissions as the permafrost thaws.
[src:arctic/arctic] The melting of Greenland's ice sheet is linked to polar amplification.
[src:arctic/arctic] Due to the poleward migration of the planet's isotherms (about 56 km (35 mi) per decade during the past 30 years as a consequence of global warming), the Arctic region (as defined by tree line and temperature) is currently shrinking.
[src:arctic/arctic] Perhaps the most alarming result of this is Arctic sea ice shrinkage.
[src:arctic/arctic] There is a large variance in predictions of Arctic sea ice loss, with models showing near-complete to complete loss in September from 2035 to sometime around 2067.
[src:arctic/arctic] Arctic life is characterized by adaptation to short growing seasons with long periods of sunlight, and cold, dark, snow-covered winter conditions, with soil depth constrained by permafrost.
[src:arctic/arctic] In the Arctic Circle, up to 24 hours of daylight is experienced at the summer solstice in June and up to 24 hours of darkness during the winter solstice in December which has an important impact on the ecology of the region.
[src:arctic/arctic] Arctic vegetation is composed of plants such as dwarf shrubs, graminoids, herbs, lichens, and mosses, which all grow relatively close to the ground, forming tundra.
[src:arctic/arctic] An example of a dwarf shrub is the bearberry.
[src:arctic/arctic] As one moves northward, the amount of warmth available for plant growth decreases considerably.
[src:arctic/arctic] In the northernmost areas, plants are at their metabolic limits, and small differences in the total amount of summer warmth make large differences in the amount of energy available for maintenance, growth, and reproduction.
[src:arctic/arctic] Colder summer temperatures cause the size, abundance, productivity, and variety of plants to decrease.
[src:arctic/arctic] Trees cannot grow in the Arctic, but in its warmest parts, shrubs are common and can reach 2 m (6 ft 7 in) in height; sedges, mosses and lichens can form thick layers.
[src:arctic/arctic] In the coldest parts of the Arctic, much of the ground is bare; non-vascular plants such as lichens and mosses predominate, along with a few scattered grasses and forbs (like the Arctic poppy).
[src:arctic/arctic] Herbivores on the tundra include the Arctic hare, lemming, muskox, and reindeer (caribou).
[src:arctic/arctic] They are preyed on by the snowy owl, Arctic fox, grizzly bear, and Arctic wolf.
[src:arctic/arctic] The polar bear is also a predator, though it prefers to hunt for marine life from the ice.
[src:arctic/arctic] There are also many birds (some 200 species breed in the Arctic) and marine species endemic to the colder regions.
[src:arctic/arctic] Other terrestrial animals include wolverines, moose, Dall sheep, ermines, and Arctic ground squirrels.
[src:arctic/arctic] Marine mammals include seals, walruses, and several species of cetacean—baleen whales and also narwhals, orcas, and belugas.
[src:arctic/arctic] There are copious natural resources in the Arctic (oil, gas, minerals, freshwater, fish, and, if the subarctic is included, forest) to which modern technology and the economic opening up of Russia have given significant new opportunities.
[src:arctic/arctic] The interest in the tourism industry is also on the increase.
[src:arctic/arctic] The Arctic contains some of the last and most extensive continuous wilderness areas in the world, and its significance in preserving biodiversity and genotypes is considerable.
[src:arctic/arctic] The increasing presence of humans fragments vital habitats.
[src:arctic/arctic] The Arctic is particularly susceptible to the abrasion of groundcover and to the disturbance of the rare breeding grounds of the animals that are characteristic of the region.
[src:arctic/arctic] The Arctic also holds 1/5 of the Earth's water supply.
[src:arctic/arctic] During the Cretaceous period, the Arctic still had seasonal snows, though only a light dusting and not enough to permanently hinder plant growth.
[src:arctic/arctic] Animals such as the *Chasmosaurus*, *Hypacrosaurus*, *Troodon*, and *Edmontosaurus* may have all migrated north to take advantage of the summer growing season, and migrated south to warmer climes when winter came.
[src:arctic/arctic] A similar situation may also have been found amongst dinosaurs that lived in Antarctic regions, such as the *Muttaburrasaurus* of Australia.
[src:arctic/arctic] However, others claim that dinosaurs lived year-round at very high latitudes, such as near the Colville River, which is now at about 70° N but at the time (70 million years ago) was 10° further north.
[src:arctic/arctic] The earliest inhabitants of North America's central and eastern Arctic are referred to as the Arctic small tool tradition (AST) and existed c.
[src:arctic/arctic] AST consisted of several Paleo-Eskimo cultures, including the Independence cultures and Pre-Dorset cultures.
[src:arctic/arctic] The Dorset culture (Inuktitut: *Tuniit* or *Tunit*) refers to the next inhabitants of central and eastern Arctic.
[src:arctic/arctic] The Dorset culture emerged across the North American Arctic through a gradual process of cultural and technological adaptation to changing environmental conditions and resource availability between 1050 and 500 BCE.
[src:arctic/arctic] With the exception of the Quebec / Labrador peninsula, the Dorset culture vanished around 1500 CE.
[src:arctic/arctic] Supported by genetic testing, evidence shows that descendants of the Dorset culture, known as the Sadlermiut, survived in Aivilik, Southampton and Coats Islands, until the beginning of the 20th century.
[src:arctic/arctic] The Dorset / Thule culture transition dates around the ninth–10th centuries CE.
[src:arctic/arctic] Scientists theorize that there may have been cross-contact between the two cultures with the sharing of technology, such as fashioning harpoon heads, or the Thule may have found Dorset remnants and adapted their ways with the predecessor culture.
[src:arctic/arctic] The evidence suggested that Inuit descend from the Birnirk of Siberia, through the Thule culture expanded into northern Canada and Greenland, where they genetically and culturally completely replaced the Indigenous Dorset people sometime after 1300 CE.
[src:arctic/arctic] By 1300 CE, the Inuit, present-day Arctic inhabitants and descendants of Thule culture, had settled in west Greenland and moved into east Greenland over the following century (Inughuit, Kalaallit and Tunumiit are modern Greenlandic Inuit groups descended from Thule).
[src:arctic/arctic] Over time, the Inuit have migrated throughout the Arctic regions of Eastern Russia, the United States, Canada, and Greenland.
[src:arctic/arctic] Other Circumpolar North indigenous peoples include the Chukchi, Evenks, Iñupiat, Khanty, Koryaks, Nenets, Sámi, Yukaghir, Gwichʼin, and Yupik.
[src:arctic/arctic] The council operates on a consensus basis, mostly dealing with environmental treaties and not addressing boundary or resource disputes.
[src:arctic/arctic] Though Arctic policy priorities differ, every Arctic nation is concerned about sovereignty/defense, resource development, shipping routes, and environmental protection.
[src:arctic/arctic] Much work remains on regulatory agreements regarding shipping, tourism, and resource development in Arctic waters.
[src:arctic/arctic] Arctic shipping is subject to some regulatory control through the International Code for Ships Operating in Polar Waters, adopted by the International Maritime Organization on 1 January 2017 and applies to all ships in Arctic waters over 500 tonnes.
[src:arctic/arctic] Research in the Arctic has long been a collaborative international effort, evidenced by the International Polar Year.
[src:arctic/arctic] The International Arctic Science Committee, hundreds of scientists and specialists of the Arctic Council, and the Barents Euro-Arctic Council are more examples of collaborative international Arctic research.
[src:arctic/arctic] While there are several ongoing territorial claims in the Arctic, no country owns the geographic North Pole or the region of the Arctic Ocean surrounding it.
[src:arctic/arctic] The surrounding six Arctic states that border the Arctic Ocean—Canada, the Kingdom of Denmark (with Greenland), Iceland, Norway, Russia, and the United States—are limited to a 200 nautical miles (370 km; 230 mi) exclusive economic zone (EEZ) off their coasts.
[src:arctic/arctic] Two Arctic states (Finland and Sweden) do not have direct access to the Arctic Ocean.
[src:arctic/arctic] Upon ratification of the United Nations Convention on the Law of the Sea, a country has ten years to make claims to an extended continental shelf beyond its 200 nautical mile zone.
[src:arctic/arctic] Due to this, Norway (which ratified the convention in 1996), Russia (ratified in 1997), Canada (ratified in 2003) and the Kingdom of Denmark (ratified in 2004) launched projects to establish claims that certain sectors of the Arctic seabed should belong to their territories.
[src:arctic/arctic] On 2 August 2007, two Russian bathyscaphes, MIR-1 and MIR-2, for the first time in history descended to the Arctic seabed beneath the North Pole and placed there a Russian flag made of rust-proof titanium alloy.
[src:arctic/arctic] The flag-placing, during Arktika 2007, generated commentary on and concern for a race for control of the Arctic's vast hydrocarbon resources.
[src:arctic/arctic] As of 2012, the Kingdom of Denmark is claiming the continental shelf based on the Lomonosov Ridge between Greenland and over the North Pole to the northern limit of the exclusive economic zone of Russia.
[src:arctic/arctic] The Russian Federation is also claiming a large swath of seabed along the Lomonosov Ridge but, unlike Denmark, confined its claim to its side of the Arctic region.
[src:arctic/arctic] In August 2015, Russia made a supplementary submission for the expansion of the external borders of its continental shelf in the Arctic Ocean, asserting that the eastern part of the Lomonosov Ridge and the Mendeleyev Ridge is an extension of the Eurasian continent.
[src:arctic/arctic] In August 2016, the UN Commission on the Limits of the Continental Shelf began to consider Russia's submission.
[src:arctic/arctic] Canada claims the Northwest Passage as part of its internal waters belonging to Canada, while the United States and most maritime nations regards it as an international strait, which means that foreign vessels have right of transit passage.
[src:arctic/arctic] The Arctic is a site of strategic competition between world powers, particularly Russia and NATO.
[src:arctic/arctic] Russia's Northern Fleet, stationed in the Kola Peninsula, is a major element of its nuclear deterrence strategy.
[src:arctic/arctic] Russia also conducts nuclear weapons tests on Novaya Zemlya, and has sought to promote the use of the Northern Sea Route in international maritime trade.
[src:arctic/arctic] The Trump administration has focused US attention on the Arctic, with Trump threatening to invade Greenland in 2025 and 2026, seeing direct control over it as essential to US strategic interests.
[src:arctic/arctic] In response to Trump, the United States's NATO allies have sought to divert US attention toward Russian Arctic activities and bolster their own readiness.
[src:arctic/arctic] Two strategically important straits in the Arctic are the GIUK Gap and the Bear Gap, between Svalbard and Norway.
[src:arctic/arctic] Since 1937, the larger portion of the Asian-side Arctic region has been extensively explored by Soviet and Russian crewed drifting ice stations.
[src:arctic/arctic] Between 1937 and 1991, 88 international polar crews established and occupied scientific settlements on the drift ice and were carried thousands of kilometers by the ice flow.
[src:arctic/arctic] The Arctic is comparatively clean, although there are certain ecologically difficult localized pollution problems that present a serious threat to people's health living around these pollution sources.
[src:arctic/arctic] Due to the prevailing worldwide sea and air currents, the Arctic area is the fallout region for long-range transport pollutants, and in some places, the concentrations exceed the levels of densely populated urban areas.
[src:arctic/arctic] An example of this is the phenomenon of Arctic haze, which is commonly blamed on long-range pollutants.
[src:arctic/arctic] Another example is with the bioaccumulation of PCBs (polychlorinated biphenyls) in Arctic wildlife and people.
[src:arctic/arctic] There have been many proposals to preserve the Arctic over the years.
[src:arctic/arctic] Most recently a group of states at the United Nations Conference on Sustainable Development, on 21 June 2012, proposed protecting the Arctic, similar to the Antarctic Treaty System.
[src:arctic/arctic] The initial focus of the campaign will be a UN resolution creating a global sanctuary around the pole, and a ban on oil drilling and unsustainable fishing in the Arctic.
[src:arctic/arctic] The Arctic has climate change rates that are amongst the highest in the world.
[src:arctic/arctic] Due to the major impacts to the region from climate change the near climate future of the region will be extremely different under all scenarios of warming.
[src:arctic/arctic] Decade-by-decade progression of arctic sea ice melting shows continued ice loss, with the greatest percentage loss rate experienced in the late summer and early autumn.
[src:arctic/arctic] The area of Arctic sea ice reached a minimum in September 2012, but recent years have shown less area than 2012 in other months.
[src:arctic/arctic] Late summer shows the greatest percentage loss.
[src:arctic/arctic] The effects of climate change in the Arctic include rising temperatures, loss of sea ice, and melting of the Greenland ice sheet.
[src:arctic/arctic] The Arctic near-surface temperature is increasing at a rate that is 2–3 times faster than the global average, which is referred to as Arctic amplification.
[src:arctic/arctic] Potential methane release from the region, especially through the thawing of permafrost and methane clathrates, is also a concern.
[src:arctic/arctic] Because of the amplified response of the Arctic to global warming, it is often seen as a leading indicator of global warming.
[src:arctic/arctic] The Arctic region is especially vulnerable to the effects of any climate change, as has become apparent with the reduction of sea ice in recent years.
[src:arctic/arctic] Climate models predict much greater climate change in the Arctic than the global average, resulting in significant international attention to the region.
[src:arctic/arctic] In particular, there are concerns that Arctic shrinkage, a consequence of melting glaciers and other ice in Greenland, could soon contribute to a substantial rise in sea levels worldwide.
[src:arctic/arctic] The current Arctic warming is leading to ancient carbon being released from thawing permafrost, leading to methane and carbon dioxide production by micro-organisms.
[src:arctic/arctic] Release of methane and carbon dioxide stored in permafrost could cause abrupt and severe global warming, as they are potent greenhouse gases.
[src:arctic/arctic] Climate change is also predicted to have a large impact on tundra vegetation, causing an increase of shrubs, and having a negative impact on bryophytes and lichens.
[src:arctic/arctic] Apart from concerns regarding the detrimental effects of warming in the Arctic, some potential opportunities have gained attention.
[src:arctic/arctic] The melting of the ice is making the Northwest Passage, shipping routes through the northernmost latitudes, more navigable, raising the possibility that the Arctic region will become a prime trade route.
[src:arctic/arctic] One harbinger of the opening navigability of the Arctic took place in the summer of 2016 when the Crystal Serenity successfully navigated the Northwest Passage, a first for a large cruise ship.
[src:arctic/arctic] In addition, it is believed that the Arctic seabed may contain substantial oil fields which may become accessible if the ice covering them melts.
[src:arctic/arctic] These factors have led to recent international debates as to which nations can claim sovereignty or ownership over the waters of the Arctic.
